{
  "Exponential growth produces a:": "",
  "S-shaped curve because growth slows as resources are consumed over time": "",
  "J-shaped curve because the population grows without limits": "",
  "Flat line because populations generally remain constant in stable environments": "",
  "Declining curve because resources decrease steadily with each new generation": "",
  "Exponential growth produces a J-shaped curve where the population increases at an accelerating rate because each generation has more individuals reproducing, assuming unlimited resources.": "",
  "Logistic growth produces a:": "",
  "Constantly declining curve because resource depletion causes population drops": "",
  "J-shaped curve that increases indefinitely beyond all resource limitations": "",
  "S-shaped curve that levels off at the carrying capacity (K)": "",
  "Straight line because population growth occurs at a constant linear rate": "",
  "Logistic growth produces an S-shaped (sigmoid) curve where population growth slows as resources become limited and eventually levels off at the carrying capacity (K) of the environment.": "",
  "Density-dependent limiting factors include:": "",
  "Hurricanes, earthquakes, and severe weather events that occur regardless of population density": "",
  "Temperature changes, drought cycles, and seasonal shifts that affect all organisms equally": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions, tsunamis, and geological events that impact all species in an area": "",
  "Competition, predation, disease, and parasitism that intensify as population density increases": "",
  "Density-dependent factors are biological interactions whose effects strengthen as population density rises. Competition for food, disease spread, and predation all intensify in crowded populations.": "",
  "Density-independent limiting factors include:": "",
  "Parasitism, disease transmission, and pathogen evolution that increase with closer organism contact": "",
  "Competition for food, territorial disputes, and predation that intensify in crowded populations": "",
  "Disease outbreaks, epidemic spread, and immune system decline caused by high population density": "",
  "Natural disasters, extreme weather, and habitat destruction that affect populations regardless of density": "",
  "Density-independent factors such as fires, floods, droughts, and volcanic eruptions affect populations regardless of their size. A hurricane kills the same proportion whether the population is large or small.": "",
  "r-selected species typically have:": "",
  "Very long lifespans": "",
  "Few offspring with extensive parental care": "",
  "Only one offspring per lifetime": "",
  "Many offspring with little parental care, rapid maturation, and short lifespans": "",
  "r-selected species (like insects, bacteria, and small rodents) invest in producing many offspring quickly, with little parental care. This strategy is advantageous in unstable environments.": "",
  "K-selected species typically have:": "",
  "Few offspring with significant parental investment, slow maturation, and long lifespans": "",
  "Very short lifespans with rapid reproduction cycles and minimal energy investment per offspring": "",
  "No significant need for territorial resources because they migrate constantly between habitats": "",
  "Thousands of offspring per breeding cycle with no parental care and rapid generation turnover": "",
  "K-selected species (like elephants, whales, and humans) produce few offspring but invest heavily in parental care. They thrive in stable environments near carrying capacity.": "",
  "Carrying capacity (K) is defined as:": "",
  "The maximum population size an environment can sustainably support given available resources": "",
  "The minimum population needed to survive": "",
  "The birth rate minus death rate": "",
  "The maximum growth rate of a population": "",
  "Carrying capacity (K) is the maximum number of individuals of a species that an environment can sustain indefinitely, determined by the availability of food, water, shelter, and space.": "",
  "When a population exceeds its carrying capacity, it typically experiences:": "",
  "A die-off or crash as resources are depleted beyond sustainable levels": "",
  "No measurable change because populations naturally self-regulate through behavioral adjustment": "",
  "Continued exponential growth as organisms adapt to exploit new untapped resource sources": "",
  "Increased resource availability as competition drives organisms to discover alternative food": "",
  "When populations exceed carrying capacity (overshoot), resources become depleted faster than they can regenerate, leading to increased mortality and a population crash back to or below K.": "",
  "The growth rate of a population equals:": "",
  "(Birth rate + Immigration) minus (Death rate + Emigration)": "",
  "Carrying capacity divided by time": "",
  "Only the birth rate": "",
  "Only the death rate": "",
  "Population growth rate is determined by the balance of additions (births + immigration) and losses (deaths + emigration). A positive balance means growth; negative means decline.": "",
  "A population in a new environment with unlimited resources will initially show:": "",
  "Zero growth because organisms must first adapt to the unfamiliar new environment": "",
  "Exponential (J-shaped) growth because there are no limiting factors": "",
  "Logistic growth because all populations inherently follow S-shaped growth curves": "",
  "Immediate decline as organisms struggle to establish themselves in unfamiliar territory": "",
  "When resources are abundant and there are few competitors or predators, populations grow exponentially. This is common when organisms colonize new environments with plentiful resources.": "",
  "What is carrying capacity?": "",
  "The minimum viable population size": "",
  "The weight a vehicle can carry": "",
  "The maximum speed of population growth": "",
  "The maximum population size that an environment can sustain indefinitely with its available resources": "",
  "Carrying capacity represents the long-term equilibrium population size determined by resource availability. It can change over time as environmental conditions, technology, or resource availability change.": "",
  "What is exponential growth?": "",
  "Growth that slows down over time": "",
  "Growth that only occurs in mathematics": "",
  "Growth that increases at a constant rate per unit time, producing a J-shaped curve on a graph": "",
  "Growth that stays constant": "",
  "Exponential growth occurs when a population increases by a constant proportion each generation, resulting in ever-accelerating growth that produces a characteristic J-shaped curve.": "",
  "What is logistic growth?": "",
  "Population growth that is always exponential, continuing at the same accelerating rate regardless of environmental conditions or resources": "",
  "Population growth that follows a J-shaped curve indefinitely because organisms continuously find new resources to sustain reproduction": "",
  "Population growth that decreases steadily from the very start as environmental resistance immediately limits reproduction from day one": "",
  "Population growth that starts exponentially but slows as the population approaches carrying capacity, producing an S-shaped curve": "",
  "Logistic growth models the reality that resources are limited. Growth starts fast but slows due to increasing competition and resource scarcity, leveling off at the environment's carrying capacity.": "",
  "What is a density-dependent factor?": "",
  "An environmental factor whose limiting effect on a population increases as population density increases": "",
  "A factor that affects all populations equally regardless of size": "",
  "A factor that only affects plants": "",
  "A factor related only to the physical density of soil": "",
  "Density-dependent factors have impacts proportional to population density. Disease spreads faster in dense populations, competition intensifies, and predators focus on abundant prey.": "",
  "What is a density-independent factor?": "",
  "A limiting factor that only affects dense populations because its impact is proportional to the number of organisms per unit area": "",
  "An environmental factor that affects population size regardless of population density, such as natural disasters or extreme weather": "",
  "A biological interaction between two or more species that regulates both populations through mutual dependency on shared resources": "",
  "A form of interspecific competition where multiple species compete for identical resources within the same ecological niche": "",
  "Density-independent factors impact populations regardless of their size or density. A severe drought, volcanic eruption, or flood can kill organisms whether the population is large or small.": "",
  "What does r-selected mean?": "",
  "A reproductive strategy characterized by producing many offspring quickly with little parental care, favoring rapid population growth (high r)": "",
  "A reproductive strategy focused on establishing territories near rivers and water sources, favoring aquatic habitat selection for breeding": "",
  "A classification for species that are always endangered due to their inability to adapt to changing environmental conditions over time": "",
  "A reproductive strategy of producing very few offspring with extensive parental investment, favoring offspring quality over quantity": "",
  "r-selected species maximize their intrinsic rate of increase (r) by producing many offspring rapidly. This strategy is advantageous in unpredictable environments where populations often crash.": "",
  "What does K-selected mean?": "",
  "A reproductive strategy characterized by few offspring, significant parental care, and populations that stay near carrying capacity (K)": "",
  "A reproductive strategy characterized by very short lifespans, rapid generational turnover, and large numbers of offspring per cycle": "",
  "A classification system named after the kinetic energy principle, where species are ranked by their metabolic activity levels": "",
  "A reproductive strategy limited to species that live exclusively in hot, tropical climates with consistently high resource availability": "",
  "K-selected species invest in fewer, higher-quality offspring with extensive parental care. They thrive in stable environments where populations are near carrying capacity and competition is high.": "",
  "What is a population crash (die-off)?": "",
  "A population that stays constant at a stable equilibrium level because birth rates and death rates remain perfectly balanced over time": "",
  "A sudden, sharp decline in population size, often occurring when a population overshoots its carrying capacity and resources are depleted": "",
  "A gradual, steady increase in population size over many centuries, driven by slow evolutionary improvements in resource utilization": "",
  "A population reaching exactly its carrying capacity and maintaining that number indefinitely through precise self-regulation mechanisms": "",
  "A population crash occurs when a population that has exceeded its carrying capacity (overshoot) rapidly declines due to resource depletion, starvation, disease, or other limiting factors.": "",
  "What is biotic potential?": "",
  "The maximum reproductive rate of a population under ideal conditions with unlimited resources": "",
  "The potential for a habitat to support life": "",
  "The minimum number of offspring a species can produce": "",
  "The carrying capacity of the environment": "",
  "Biotic potential (rmax) is the maximum rate at which a population can grow when resources are unlimited and environmental conditions are ideal. It varies greatly among species.": "",
  "What is environmental resistance?": "",
  "The collective environmental factors that limit population growth, including predation, disease, competition, and limited resources": "",
  "The ability of an ecosystem to resist changes in species composition and maintain its current community structure against disturbances": "",
  "An organism's immune system and physical defense mechanisms that protect it from predators, pathogens, and environmental stress": "",
  "A measurement of the physical and atmospheric forces that affect organism movement, migration patterns, and habitat distribution": "",
  "Environmental resistance is the combination of all biotic and abiotic factors that prevent a population from reaching its biotic potential, including predation, disease, limited food, and habitat constraints.": "",
  "A small island has a population of deer introduced without predators. For the first few years, the deer population grows rapidly because food is abundant. After 10 years, the population crashes dramatically. This pattern is best explained by:": "",
  "The deer migrated away from the island to nearby mainland areas following natural dispersal instincts": "",
  "The population overshot the island's carrying capacity, depleted food resources, and experienced a die-off": "",
  "The deer evolved into a smaller species better adapted to island conditions through rapid selection": "",
  "Predators were secretly introduced to the island by wildlife management officials to control numbers": "",
  "Without predators, deer experienced exponential growth, exceeded the island's carrying capacity, overgrazed vegetation, and then crashed when food became scarce. This overshoot-and-crash pattern is common.": "",
  "A wildlife biologist observes that a dense rabbit population is experiencing a disease outbreak that is spreading rapidly, while a sparse rabbit population nearby is unaffected. This difference is due to:": "",
  "The two rabbit populations being genetically distinct species with different levels of immunity to the pathogen": "",
  "Disease being a density-dependent factor that spreads more easily in crowded populations due to increased contact rates": "",
  "The disease organism specifically targeting larger, more mature rabbits that produce stronger immune responses": "",
  "Significant climate and microhabitat differences between the two geographic areas affecting pathogen survival": "",
  "Disease is a density-dependent factor because pathogens spread more easily when individuals are crowded together, increasing contact rates. Sparse populations have lower transmission rates.": "",
  "A farmer introduces a new pest insect to a greenhouse. The insect reproduces quickly, producing hundreds of eggs per week. Within a month, the greenhouse is infested. This insect is most likely:": "",
  "K-selected with few offspring and long parental care": "",
  "r-selected, producing many offspring rapidly with little parental investment to exploit the abundant resources": "",
  "A K-selected apex predator": "",
  "Not following any reproductive strategy": "",
  "Rapid reproduction with many offspring and no parental care is classic r-selection. This strategy allows species to quickly exploit new or disturbed habitats with abundant resources.": "",
  "Elephant populations grow slowly because females produce only one calf every 4-5 years, pregnancy lasts 22 months, and calves require years of parental care. This reproductive strategy makes elephants especially vulnerable to:": "",
  "Competition from r-selected species": "",
  "Nothing, because they are large animals": "",
  "Only climate change": "",
  "Poaching and habitat loss, because their slow reproduction cannot replace losses quickly": "",
  "K-selected species like elephants reproduce slowly, so population declines from poaching or habitat loss cannot be quickly recovered. This makes conservation efforts critical for their survival.": "",
  "A lake has a fish population of 500 with a birth rate of 100/year, death rate of 60/year, immigration of 20/year, and emigration of 10/year. The population growth for the year is:": "",
  "200 fish (calculated as births plus immigration: 100 + 20 = 120, plus natural population growth factor)": "",
  "0 fish (births minus deaths equals 40, fully offset by net emigration of 40, resulting in zero change)": "",
  "50 fish (births + immigration - deaths - emigration = 100 + 20 - 60 - 10)": "",
  "100 fish (calculated using only the birth rate of 100 as the sole factor in population growth)": "",
  "Population change equals (births + immigration) - (deaths + emigration) = (100 + 20) - (60 + 10) = 50 fish. The population would grow from 500 to 550 that year.": "",
  "A volcanic eruption destroys a forest, killing 90% of all organisms regardless of how many were present. This disaster is an example of:": "",
  "Predation, since the volcanic eruption functions like a predator by selectively eliminating weaker organisms": "",
  "A density-independent factor because it affects the population regardless of its size or density": "",
  "A density-dependent factor because denser populations suffered proportionally greater losses from the eruption": "",
  "Competition, because organisms competed for the remaining safe spaces and resources after the eruption": "",
  "Volcanic eruptions are density-independent because they destroy organisms regardless of population density. Whether the forest had 100 or 10,000 organisms, the eruption would kill the same proportion.": "",
  "Scientists studying a wolf-moose system on an island notice that when moose populations are high, wolves thrive and increase. More wolves then reduce moose numbers, which causes wolf numbers to decline, allowing moose to recover. This cycling pattern demonstrates:": "",
  "Density-independent factors controlling both populations": "",
  "That wolves and moose never interact": "",
  "Density-dependent regulation through predator-prey dynamics creating oscillating population cycles": "",
  "That moose are r-selected species": "",
  "The wolf-moose system on Isle Royale is a classic example of density-dependent predator-prey cycling, where populations of predator and prey oscillate in response to each other's abundance.": "",
  "An ecologist studying bacteria notices that when placed in a petri dish with limited nutrients, the bacterial population initially grows exponentially, then slows, and finally levels off. The population at which growth stops represents:": "",
  "The carrying capacity of the petri dish, limited by nutrient availability and waste accumulation": "",
  "The extinction threshold, the critical population level below which the bacteria cannot sustain themselves": "",
  "Exponential growth continuing at a slower rate, with bacteria adapting to utilize nutrients more efficiently": "",
  "The minimum viable population, the smallest number of bacteria needed to maintain a self-sustaining colony": "",
  "The leveling-off point represents carrying capacity (K), where the bacteria population has grown to the maximum size the dish can support given its nutrient supply and waste absorption capacity.": "",
  "A conservation biologist discovers that a population of endangered pandas has only 50 individuals left. Even with habitat protection, the population faces increased risk because:": "",
  "Pandas do not need genetic diversity": "",
  "50 is too many pandas for any habitat": "",
  "Small populations face inbreeding, genetic drift, vulnerability to catastrophic events, and difficulty finding mates": "",
  "Small populations grow faster than large ones": "",
  "Small populations are vulnerable to extinction vortices: inbreeding reduces genetic diversity, random events can eliminate the entire population, and finding mates becomes difficult, all reducing viability.": "",
  "A city park has a population of Canada geese that has grown so large they are degrading the park's grass and polluting the pond. A wildlife manager suggests using egg addling (preventing eggs from hatching) rather than culling. This approach addresses the population issue by:": "",
  "Encouraging geese to emigrate to other parks by reducing available food sources and nesting habitat": "",
  "Increasing the death rate through introduction of natural predators such as foxes or coyotes into the park": "",
  "Increasing the carrying capacity of the park by expanding habitat area and planting additional vegetation": "",
  "Reducing the birth rate to slow population growth without harming adult birds, gradually bringing the population below carrying capacity": "",
  "Egg addling is a humane population management tool that reduces the birth rate, gradually decreasing the population size to match the park's carrying capacity without directly killing adult geese.": ""
}